{
  "doc_id": "42366",
  "text": "The maturation state of DCs has major implications on antigen processing and cell trafficking and may be critical to better understand the role of DCs in prion pathogenesis. Even though immature DCs are poor in T cell priming, they are efficient in antigen capture and processing [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Migration is greatly affected by the maturation state of DCs and immature and activated DCs are recruited by distinct chemokines [CITATION_3] . Upregulation of CCR7 during maturation renders DCs sensitive to the chemoattractants CCL19/CCL21 [CITATION_4] and are consequently recruited to T-cell rich areas [CITATION_5] . Accordingly, mice with a recessive loss of CCL21 and CCL19 expression showed defects in the migration of naïve T cells and activated DCs [CITATION_6] . When inoculated with mouse prions, however, these mice only showed marginal effects on disease incubation times, indicating that CCL19/CCL21-dependent DC migration to T-cell zones does not seem to contribute to prion accumulation in lymphoid organs [CITATION_7] .",
